[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p01] The goal of logistic regression is to use the dataset to create a predictive model of the outcome variable.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p01] As in linear regression, the outcome variables *Y**i* are assumed to depend on the explanatory variables *x*1,*i* ...
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p01] The explanatory variables may be of any type: real-valued, binary, categorical, etc.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p01] The main distinction is between continuous variables and discrete variables.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p01] Formally, the outcomes *Y**i* are described as being Bernoulli-distributed data, where each outcome is determined by an unobserved probability *p**i* that is specific to the outcome at hand, but related to the explanatory variables.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p01] The second line expresses the fact that the expected value of each *Y**i* is equal to the probability of success *p**i*, which is a general property of the Bernoulli distribution.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p01] In other words, if we run a large number of Bernoulli trials using the same probability of success *p**i*, then take the average of all the 1 and 0 outcomes, then the result would be close to *p**i*.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p01] This is because doing an average this way simply computes the proportion of successes seen, which we expect to converge to the underlying probability of success.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p01] The third line writes out the probability mass function of the Bernoulli distribution, specifying the probability of seeing each of the two possible outcomes.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p01] The fourth line is another way of writing the probability mass function, which avoids having to write separate cases and is more convenient for certain types of calculations.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p01] This relies on the fact that *Y**i* can take only the value 0 or 1.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p01] In each case, one of the exponents will be 1, "choosing" the value under it, while the other is 0, "canceling out" the value under it.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p01] Hence, the outcome is either *p**i* or 1 − *p**i*, as in the previous line.
