[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] There are various equivalent specifications and interpretations of logistic regression, which fit into different types of more general models, and allow different generalizations.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] This formulation expresses logistic regression as a type of generalized linear model, which predicts variables with various types of probability distributions by fitting a linear predictor function of the above form to some sort of arbitrary transformation of the expected value of the variable.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The intuition for transforming using the logit function (the natural log of the odds) was explained above.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] It also has the practical effect of converting the probability (which is bounded to be between 0 and 1) to a variable that ranges over $(-\infty ,+\infty )$ — thereby matching the potential range of the linear prediction function on the right side of the equation.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Both the probabilities *p**i* and the regression coefficients are unobserved, and the means of determining them is not part of the model itself.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The use of a regularization condition is equivalent to doing maximum a posteriori (MAP) estimation, an extension of maximum likelihood.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The interpretation of the *β**j* parameter estimates is as the additive effect on the log of the odds for a unit change in the *j* the explanatory variable.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In the case of a dichotomous explanatory variable, for instance, gender $e^{\beta }$ is the estimate of the odds of having the outcome for, say, males compared with females.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The logistic model has an equivalent formulation as a latent-variable model.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] This formulation is common in the theory of discrete choice models and makes it easier to extend to certain more complicated models with multiple, correlated choices, as well as to compare logistic regression to the closely related probit model.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] i.e. the latent variable can be written directly in terms of the linear predictor function and an additive random error variable that is distributed according to a standard logistic distribution.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The choice of modeling the error variable specifically with a standard logistic distribution, rather than a general logistic distribution with the location and scale set to arbitrary values, seems restrictive, but in fact, it is not.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] It must be kept in mind that we can choose the regression coefficients ourselves, and very often can use them to offset changes in the parameters of the error variable's distribution.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] For example, a logistic error-variable distribution with a non-zero location parameter *μ* (which sets the mean) is equivalent to a distribution with a zero location parameter, where *μ* has been added to the intercept coefficient.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Both situations produce the same value for *Y**i** regardless of settings of explanatory variables.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Similarly, an arbitrary scale parameter *s* is equivalent to setting the scale parameter to 1 and then dividing all regression coefficients by *s*.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In the latter case, the resulting value of *Y**i**** will be smaller by a factor of *s* than in the former case, for all sets of explanatory variables — but critically, it will always remain on the same side of 0, and hence lead to the same *Y**i* choice.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] It turns out that this formulation is exactly equivalent to the preceding one, phrased in terms of the generalized linear model and without any latent variables.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] This can be shown as follows, using the fact that the cumulative distribution function (CDF) of the standard logistic distribution is the logistic function, which is the inverse of the logit function, i.e.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] This formulation—which is standard in discrete choice models—makes clear the relationship between logistic regression (the "logit model") and the probit model, which uses an error variable distributed according to a standard normal distribution instead of a standard logistic distribution.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Both the logistic and normal distributions are symmetric with a basic unimodal, "bell curve" shape.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The only difference is that the logistic distribution has somewhat heavier tails, which means that it is less sensitive to outlying data (and hence somewhat more robust to model mis-specifications or erroneous data).
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] where *EV*1(0,1) is a standard type-1 extreme value distribution: i.e.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] This model has a separate latent variable and a separate set of regression coefficients for each possible outcome of the dependent variable.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The reason for this separation is that it makes it easy to extend logistic regression to multi-outcome categorical variables, as in the multinomial logit model.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In such a model, it is natural to model each possible outcome using a different set of regression coefficients.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] It is also possible to motivate each of the separate latent variables as the theoretical utility associated with making the associated choice, and thus motivate logistic regression in terms of utility theory.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The choice of the type-1 extreme value distribution seems fairly arbitrary, but it makes the mathematics work out, and it may be possible to justify its use through rational choice theory.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] It turns out that this model is equivalent to the previous model, although this seems non-obvious, since there are now two sets of regression coefficients and error variables, and the error variables have a different distribution.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] An intuition for this comes from the fact that, since we choose based on the maximum of two values, only their difference matters, not the exact values — and this effectively removes one degree of freedom.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Yet another formulation combines the two-way latent variable formulation above with the original formulation higher up without latent variables, and in the process provides a link to one of the standard formulations of the multinomial logit.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Two separate sets of regression coefficients have been introduced, just as in the two-way latent variable model, and the two equations appear a form that writes the logarithm of the associated probability as a linear predictor, with an extra term $-\ln Z$ at the end.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] This term, as it turns out, serves as the normalizing factor ensuring that the result is a distribution.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In this form it is clear that the purpose of *Z* is to ensure that the resulting distribution over *Y**i* is in fact a probability distribution, i.e. it sums to 1.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] This means that *Z* is simply the sum of all un-normalized probabilities, and by dividing each probability by *Z*, the probabilities become "normalized".
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] This shows clearly how to generalize this formulation to more than two outcomes, as in multinomial logit.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] To prove that this is equivalent to the previous model, we start by recognizing the above model is overspecified, in that $\Pr(Y_{i}=0)$ and $\Pr(Y_{i}=1)$ cannot be independently specified: rather $\Pr(Y_{i}=0)+\Pr(Y_{i}=1)=1$ so knowing one automatically determines the other.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] As a result, the model is nonidentifiable, in that multiple combinations of ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}_{0}$ and ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}_{1}$ will produce the same probabilities for all possible explanatory variables.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] As a result, we can simplify matters, and restore identifiability, by picking an arbitrary value for one of the two vectors.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] which shows that this formulation is indeed equivalent to the previous formulation.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Most treatments of the multinomial logit model start out either by extending the "log-linear" formulation presented here or the two-way latent variable formulation presented above, since both clearly show the way that the model could be extended to multi-way outcomes.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In general, the presentation with latent variables is more common in econometrics and political science, where discrete choice models and utility theory reign, while the "log-linear" formulation here is more common in computer science, e.g. machine learning and natural language processing.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] This functional form is commonly called a single-layer perceptron or single-layer artificial neural network.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] A single-layer neural network computes a continuous output instead of a step function.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] where *f*(*X*) is an analytic function in *X*.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] With this choice, the single-layer neural network is identical to the logistic regression model.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] This function has a continuous derivative, which allows it to be used in backpropagation.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] An example of this distribution is the fraction of seeds (*p**i*) that germinate after *n**i* are planted.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] This model can be fit using the same sorts of methods as the above more basic model.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The regression coefficients are usually estimated using maximum likelihood estimation.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Unlike linear regression with normally distributed residuals, it is not possible to find a closed-form expression for the coefficient values that maximize the likelihood function so an iterative process must be used instead; for example Newton's method.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] This process begins with a tentative solution, revises it slightly to see if it can be improved, and repeats this revision until no more improvement is made, at which point the process is said to have converged.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In some instances, the model may not reach convergence.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Non-convergence of a model indicates that the coefficients are not meaningful because the iterative process was unable to find appropriate solutions.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] A failure to converge may occur for a number of reasons: having a large ratio of predictors to cases, multicollinearity, sparseness, or complete separation.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Binary logistic regression ( $y=0$ or $y=1$ ) can, for example, be calculated using *iteratively reweighted least squares* (IRLS), which is equivalent to maximizing the log-likelihood of a Bernoulli distributed process using Newton's method.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] the regressor matrix and $\mathbf {y} (i)=[y(1),y(2),\ldots ]^{T}$ the vector of response variables.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] More details can be found in the literature.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In a Bayesian statistics context, prior distributions are normally placed on the regression coefficients, for example in the form of Gaussian distributions.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] There is no conjugate prior of the likelihood function in logistic regression.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] When Bayesian inference was performed analytically, this made the posterior distribution difficult to calculate except in very low dimensions.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Now, though, automatic software such as OpenBUGS, JAGS, PyMC, Stan or Turing.jl allows these posteriors to be computed using simulation, so lack of conjugacy is not a concern.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] However, when the sample size or the number of parameters is large, full Bayesian simulation can be slow, and people often use approximate methods such as variational Bayesian methods and expectation propagation.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Widely used, the "one in ten rule", states that logistic regression models give stable values for the explanatory variables if based on a minimum of about 10 events per explanatory variable (EPV); where *event* denotes the cases belonging to the less frequent category in the dependent variable.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Thus a study designed to use k explanatory variables for an event (e.g. myocardial infarction) expected to occur in a proportion p of participants in the study will require a total of $10k/p$ participants.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] However, there is considerable debate about the reliability of this rule, which is based on simulation studies and lacks a secure theoretical underpinning.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The worst instances of each problem were not severe with 5–9 EPV and usually comparable to those with 10–16 EPV".
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Others have found results that are not consistent with the above, using different criteria.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] A useful criterion is whether the fitted model will be expected to achieve the same predictive discrimination in a new sample as it appeared to achieve in the model development sample.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] For that criterion, 20 events per candidate variable may be required.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Also, one can argue that 96 observations are needed only to estimate the model's intercept precisely enough that the margin of error in predicted probabilities is ±0.1 with a 0.95 confidence level.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In any fitting procedure, the addition of another fitting parameter to a model (e.g. the beta parameters in a logistic regression model) will almost always improve the ability of the model to predict the measured outcomes.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] This will be true even if the additional term has no predictive value, since the model will simply be "overfitting" to the noise in the data.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The question arises as to whether the improvement gained by the addition of another fitting parameter is significant enough to recommend the inclusion of the additional term, or whether the improvement is simply that which may be expected from overfitting.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In short, for logistic regression, a statistic known as the deviance is defined which is a measure of the error between the logistic model fit and the outcome data.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In the limit of a large number of data points, the deviance is chi-squared distributed, which allows a chi-squared test to be implemented in order to determine the significance of the explanatory variables.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Linear regression and logistic regression have many similarities.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] For example, in simple linear regression, a set of *K* data points (*xk*, *yk*) are fitted to a proposed model function of the form $y=b_{0}+b_{1}x$ .
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The fitting process consists of choosing a value of *b*0 which minimizes $\varepsilon ^{2}$ of the fit to the null model, denoted by $\varepsilon _{\varphi }^{2}$ where the $\varphi$ subscript denotes the null model.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] which is proportional to the square of the (uncorrected) sample standard deviation of the *yk* data points.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] We can imagine a case where the *yk* data points are randomly assigned to the various *xk*, and then fitted using the proposed model.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Specifically, we can consider the fits of the proposed model to every permutation of the *yk* outcomes.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] For logistic regression, the measure of goodness-of-fit is the likelihood function *L*, or its logarithm, the log-likelihood *ℓ*.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The likelihood function *L* is analogous to the $\varepsilon ^{2}$ in the linear regression case, except that the likelihood is maximized rather than minimized.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Denote the maximized log-likelihood of the proposed model by ${\hat {\ell }}$ .
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] where ⁠ $p(x)$ ⁠ is the probability that $y=1$ .
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] where ${\overline {y}}$ is again the mean of the *yk* values.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Using the chi-squared test of significance, the integral of the chi-squared distribution with one degree of freedom from 11.6661... to infinity is equal to 0.00063649...
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] This effectively means that about 6 out of a 10,000 fits to random *yk* can be expected to have a better fit (smaller deviance) than the given *yk* and so we can conclude that the inclusion of the *x* variable and data in the proposed model is a very significant improvement over the null model.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In other words, we reject the null hypothesis with $1-D\approx 99.94\%$ confidence.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Goodness of fit in linear regression models is generally measured using R2.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Since this has no direct analog in logistic regression, various methods including the following can be used instead.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In linear regression analysis, one is concerned with partitioning variance via the sum of squares calculations – variance in the criterion is essentially divided into variance accounted for by the predictors and residual variance.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In logistic regression analysis, deviance is used in lieu of a sum of squares calculations.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Deviance is analogous to the sum of squares calculations in linear regression and is a measure of the lack of fit to the data in a logistic regression model.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] When a "saturated" model is available (a model with a theoretically perfect fit), deviance is calculated by comparing a given model with the saturated model.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In the above equation, D represents the deviance and ln represents the natural logarithm.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The log of this likelihood ratio (the ratio of the fitted model to the saturated model) will produce a negative value, hence the need for a negative sign.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] D can be shown to follow an approximate chi-squared distribution.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Smaller values indicate better fit as the fitted model deviates less from the saturated model.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] When assessed upon a chi-square distribution, nonsignificant chi-square values indicate very little unexplained variance and thus, good model fit.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Conversely, a significant chi-square value indicates that a significant amount of the variance is unexplained.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] When the saturated model is not available (a common case), deviance is calculated simply as −2·(log likelihood of the fitted model), and the reference to the saturated model's log likelihood can be removed from all that follows without harm.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Two measures of deviance are particularly important in logistic regression: null deviance and model deviance.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The null deviance represents the difference between a model with only the intercept (which means "no predictors") and the saturated model.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The model deviance represents the difference between a model with at least one predictor and the saturated model.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In this respect, the null model provides a baseline upon which to compare predictor models.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Given that deviance is a measure of the difference between a given model and the saturated model, smaller values indicate better fit.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Thus, to assess the contribution of a predictor or set of predictors, one can subtract the model deviance from the null deviance and assess the difference on a $\chi _{s-p}^{2},$ chi-square distribution with degrees of freedom equal to the difference in the number of parameters estimated.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] If the model deviance is significantly smaller than the null deviance then one can conclude that the predictor or set of predictors significantly improve the model's fit.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] This is analogous to the F-test used in linear regression analysis to assess the significance of prediction.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In linear regression the squared multiple correlation, R2 is used to assess goodness of fit as it represents the proportion of variance in the criterion that is explained by the predictors.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In logistic regression analysis, there is no agreed upon analogous measure, but there are several competing measures each with limitations.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The Hosmer–Lemeshow test uses a test statistic that asymptotically follows a $\chi ^{2}$ distribution to assess whether or not the observed event rates match expected event rates in subgroups of the model population.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] This test is considered to be obsolete by some statisticians because of its dependence on arbitrary binning of predicted probabilities and relative low power.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] After fitting the model, it is likely that researchers will want to examine the contribution of individual predictors.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] To do so, they will want to examine the regression coefficients.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In linear regression, the regression coefficients represent the change in the criterion for each unit change in the predictor.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In logistic regression, however, the regression coefficients represent the change in the logit for each unit change in the predictor.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Given that the logit is not intuitive, researchers are likely to focus on a predictor's effect on the exponential function of the regression coefficient – the odds ratio (see definition).
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In linear regression, the significance of a regression coefficient is assessed by computing a *t* test.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In logistic regression, there are several different tests designed to assess the significance of an individual predictor, most notably the likelihood ratio test and the Wald statistic.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The likelihood-ratio test discussed above to assess model fit is also the recommended procedure to assess the contribution of individual "predictors" to a given model.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In the case of a single predictor model, one simply compares the deviance of the predictor model with that of the null model on a chi-square distribution with a single degree of freedom.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] If the predictor model has significantly smaller deviance (c.f. chi-square using the difference in degrees of freedom of the two models), then one can conclude that there is a significant association between the "predictor" and the outcome.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Although some common statistical packages (e.g.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] SPSS) do provide likelihood ratio test statistics, without this computationally intensive test it would be more difficult to assess the contribution of individual predictors in the multiple logistic regression case.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] To assess the contribution of individual predictors one can enter the predictors hierarchically, comparing each new model with the previous to determine the contribution of each predictor.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] There is some debate among statisticians about the appropriateness of so-called "stepwise" procedures.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The fear is that they may not preserve nominal statistical properties and may become misleading.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Alternatively, when assessing the contribution of individual predictors in a given model, one may examine the significance of the Wald statistic.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The Wald statistic, analogous to the *t*-test in linear regression, is used to assess the significance of coefficients.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The Wald statistic is the ratio of the square of the regression coefficient to the square of the standard error of the coefficient and is asymptotically distributed as a chi-square distribution.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Although several statistical packages (e.g., SPSS, SAS) report the Wald statistic to assess the contribution of individual predictors, the Wald statistic has limitations.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] When the regression coefficient is large, the standard error of the regression coefficient also tends to be larger increasing the probability of Type-II error.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The Wald statistic also tends to be biased when data are sparse.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Then we might wish to sample them more frequently than their prevalence in the population.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] For example, suppose there is a disease that affects 1 person in 10,000 and to collect our data we need to do a complete physical.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] It may be too expensive to do thousands of physicals of healthy people in order to obtain data for only a few diseased individuals.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Thus, we may evaluate more diseased individuals, perhaps all of the rare outcomes.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] This is also retrospective sampling, or equivalently it is called unbalanced data.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] As a rule of thumb, sampling controls at a rate of five times the number of cases will produce sufficient control data.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Logistic regression is unique in that it may be estimated on unbalanced data, rather than randomly sampled data, and still yield correct coefficient estimates of the effects of each independent variable on the outcome.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] That is to say, if we form a logistic model from such data, if the model is correct in the general population, the $\beta _{j}$ parameters are all correct except for $\beta _{0}$ .
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] where $\pi$ is the true prevalence and ${\tilde {\pi }}$ is the prevalence in the sample.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Like other forms of regression analysis, logistic regression makes use of one or more predictor variables that may be either continuous or categorical.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Unlike ordinary linear regression, however, logistic regression is used for predicting dependent variables that take membership in one of a limited number of categories (treating the dependent variable in the binomial case as the outcome of a Bernoulli trial) rather than a continuous outcome.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Given this difference, the assumptions of linear regression are violated.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In particular, the residuals cannot be normally distributed.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In addition, linear regression may make nonsensical predictions for a binary dependent variable.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] What is needed is a way to convert a binary variable into a continuous one that can take on any real value (negative or positive).
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] To do that, binomial logistic regression first calculates the odds of the event happening for different levels of each independent variable, and then takes its logarithm to create a continuous criterion as a transformed version of the dependent variable.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Although the dependent variable in logistic regression is Bernoulli, the logit is on an unrestricted scale.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Y is the Bernoulli-distributed response variable and x is the predictor variable; the β values are the linear parameters.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The logit of the probability of success is then fitted to the predictors.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The predicted value of the logit is converted back into predicted odds, via the inverse of the natural logarithm – the exponential function.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Thus, although the observed dependent variable in binary logistic regression is a 0-or-1 variable, the logistic regression estimates the odds, as a continuous variable, that the dependent variable is a 'success'.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In some applications, the odds are all that is needed.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In others, a specific yes-or-no prediction is needed for whether the dependent variable is or is not a 'success'; this categorical prediction can be based on the computed odds of success, with predicted odds above some chosen cutoff value being translated into a prediction of success.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] In machine learning applications where logistic regression is used for binary classification, the MLE minimises the cross-entropy loss function.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Logistic regression is an important machine learning algorithm.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] The goal is to model the probability of a random variable Y being 0 or 1 given experimental data.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] which is maximized using optimization techniques such as gradient descent.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] where $H(Y\mid X)$ is the conditional entropy and $D_{\text{KL}}$ is the Kullback–Leibler divergence.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] This leads to the intuition that by maximizing the log-likelihood of a model, you are minimizing the KL divergence of your model from the maximal entropy distribution.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p02] Intuitively searching for the model that makes the fewest assumptions in its parameters.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] Logistic regression can be seen as a special case of the generalized linear model and thus analogous to linear regression.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] The model of logistic regression, however, is based on quite different assumptions (about the relationship between the dependent and independent variables) from those of linear regression.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] In particular, the key differences between these two models can be seen in the following two features of logistic regression.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] First, the conditional distribution $y\mid x$ is a Bernoulli distribution rather than a Gaussian distribution, because the dependent variable is binary.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] Second, the predicted values are probabilities and are therefore restricted to (0,1) through the logistic distribution function because logistic regression predicts the **probability** of particular outcomes rather than the outcomes themselves.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] A common alternative to the logistic model (logit model) is the probit model, as the related names suggest.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] From the perspective of generalized linear models, these differ in the choice of link function: the logistic model uses the logit function (inverse logistic function), while the probit model uses the probit function (inverse error function).
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] Equivalently, in the latent variable interpretations of these two methods, the first assumes a standard logistic distribution of errors and the second a standard normal distribution of errors.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] Other sigmoid functions or error distributions can be used instead.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] Logistic regression is an alternative to Fisher's 1936 method, linear discriminant analysis.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] If the assumptions of linear discriminant analysis hold, the conditioning can be reversed to produce logistic regression.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] The converse is not true, however, because logistic regression does not require the multivariate normal assumption of discriminant analysis.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] The assumption of linear predictor effects can easily be relaxed using techniques such as spline functions.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] A detailed history of the logistic regression is given in Cramer (2002).
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] The logistic function was developed as a model of population growth and named "logistic" by Pierre François Verhulst in the 1830s and 1840s, under the guidance of Adolphe Quetelet; see Logistic function § History for details.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] In his earliest paper (1838), Verhulst did not specify how he fit the curves to the data.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] In his more detailed paper (1845), Verhulst determined the three parameters of the model by making the curve pass through three observed points, which yielded poor predictions.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] The logistic function was independently developed in chemistry as a model of autocatalysis (Wilhelm Ostwald, 1883).
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] An autocatalytic reaction is one in which one of the products is itself a catalyst for the same reaction, while the supply of one of the reactants is fixed.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] This naturally gives rise to the logistic equation for the same reason as population growth: the reaction is self-reinforcing but constrained.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] The logistic function was independently rediscovered as a model of population growth in 1920 by Raymond Pearl and Lowell Reed, published as Pearl & Reed (1920), which led to its use in modern statistics.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] They were initially unaware of Verhulst's work and presumably learned about it from L.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] Gustave du Pasquier, but they gave him little credit and did not adopt his terminology.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] Verhulst's priority was acknowledged and the term "logistic" revived by Udny Yule in 1925 and has been followed since.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] Pearl and Reed first applied the model to the population of the United States, and also initially fitted the curve by making it pass through three points; as with Verhulst, this again yielded poor results.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] In the 1930s, the probit model was developed and systematized by Chester Ittner Bliss, who coined the term "probit" in Bliss (1934), and by John Gaddum in Gaddum (1933), and the model fit by maximum likelihood estimation by Ronald A.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] Fisher in Fisher (1935), as an addendum to Bliss's work.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] The probit model was principally used in bioassay, and had been preceded by earlier work dating to 1860; see Probit model § History.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] The probit model influenced the subsequent development of the logit model and these models competed with each other.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] The logistic model was likely first used as an alternative to the probit model in bioassay by Edwin Bidwell Wilson and his student Jane Worcester in Wilson & Worcester (1943).
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] However, the development of the logistic model as a general alternative to the probit model was principally due to the work of Joseph Berkson over many decades, beginning in Berkson (1944), where he coined "logit", by analogy with "probit", and continuing through Berkson (1951) and following years.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] The logit model was initially dismissed as inferior to the probit model, but "gradually achieved an equal footing with the probit", particularly between 1960 and 1970.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] By 1970, the logit model achieved parity with the probit model in use in statistics journals and thereafter surpassed it.
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] Various refinements occurred during that time, notably by David Cox, as in Cox (1958).
[src:statsmodels/logistic-regression-p03] The multinomial logit model was introduced independently in Cox (1966) and Theil (1969), which greatly increased the scope of application and the popularity of the logit model.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Some sources consider OLS to be linear regression.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Geometrically, this is seen as the sum of the squared distances, parallel to the axis of the dependent variable, between each data point in the set and the corresponding point on the regression surface—the smaller the differences, the better the model fits the data.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The resulting estimator can be expressed by a simple formula, especially in the case of a simple linear regression, in which there is a single regressor on the right side of the regression equation.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Under these conditions, the method of OLS provides minimum-variance mean-unbiased estimation when the errors have finite variances.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Under the additional assumption that the errors are normally distributed with zero mean, OLS is the maximum likelihood estimator that outperforms any non-linear unbiased estimator.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Each observation i includes a scalar response $y_{i}$ and a column vector $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ of p parameters (regressors), i.e., $\mathbf {x} _{i}=\left[x_{i1},x_{i2},\dots ,x_{ip}\right]^{\operatorname {T} }$ .
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Typically, a constant term is included in the set of regressors $\mathbf {X}$ , say, by taking $x_{i1}=1$ for all $i=1,\dots ,n$ .
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The coefficient $\beta _{1}$ corresponding to this regressor is called the *intercept*.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Without the intercept, the fitted line is forced to cross the origin when $x_{i}={\vec {0}}$ .
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Regressors do not have to be independent for estimation to be consistent e.g. they may be non-linearly dependent.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Short of perfect multicollinearity, parameter estimates may still be consistent; however, as multicollinearity rises the standard error around such estimates increases and reduces the precision of such estimates.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] When there is perfect multicollinearity, it is no longer possible to obtain unique estimates for the coefficients to the related regressors; estimation for these parameters cannot converge (thus, it cannot be consistent).
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] As a concrete example where regressors are non-linearly dependent yet estimation may still be consistent, we might suspect the response depends linearly both on a value and its square; in which case we would include one regressor whose value is just the square of another regressor.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In that case, the model would be *quadratic* in the second regressor, but none-the-less is still considered a *linear* model because the model *is* still linear in the parameters ( ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ ).
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] of n linear equations in p unknown coefficients, $\beta _{1},\beta _{2},\dots ,\beta _{p}$ , with $n>p$ .
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] (Note: for a linear model as above, not all elements in $\mathbf {X}$ contains information on the data points.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The first column is populated with ones, $X_{i1}=1$ .
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Only the other columns contain actual data.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] So here p is equal to the number of regressors plus one).
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] A justification for choosing this criterion is given in Properties below.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The matrix $\mathbf {X} ^{\operatorname {T} }\mathbf {X}$ is known as the *normal matrix* or Gram matrix and the matrix $\mathbf {X} ^{\operatorname {T} }\mathbf {y}$ is known as the moment matrix of regressand by regressors.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Suppose *b* is a "candidate" value for the parameter vector *β*.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The quantity *yi* − *xi*T*b*, called the *residual* for the *i*-th observation, measures the vertical distance between the data point (*xi*, *yi*) and the hyperplane *y* = *x*T*b*, and thus assesses the degree of fit between the actual data and the model.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *T* denotes the matrix transpose, and the rows of *X*, denoting the values of all the independent variables associated with a particular value of the dependent variable, are *Xi = xi*T.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The value of *b* which minimizes this sum is called the **OLS estimator for *β***.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The product *N* = *X*T *X* is a Gram matrix, and its inverse, *Q* = *N*−1, is the *cofactor matrix* of *β*, closely related to its covariance matrix, *C**β*.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The matrix (*X*T *X*)−1 *X*T = *Q* *X*T is called the Moore–Penrose pseudoinverse matrix of *X*.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This formulation highlights the point that estimation can be carried out if, and only if, there is no perfect multicollinearity between the explanatory variables (which would cause the Gram matrix to have no inverse).
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *P* = *X*(*X*T*X*)−1*X*T is the *projection matrix* onto the space *V* spanned by the columns of *X*.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This matrix *P* is also sometimes called the *hat matrix* because it "puts a hat" onto the variable *y*.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Another matrix, closely related to *P* is the *annihilator* matrix *M* = *In* − *P*; this is a projection matrix onto the space orthogonal to *V*.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Both matrices *P* and *M* are symmetric and idempotent (meaning that *P*2 = *P* and *M*2 = *M*), and relate to the data matrix *X* via identities *PX* = *X* and *MX* = 0.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *P* is the projection matrix and *s*2 is the sample variance.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *X*i is the *i*-th row of matrix *X*.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The denominator, *n*−*p*, is the statistical degrees of freedom.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The first quantity, *s*2, is the OLS estimate for *σ*2, whereas the second, $\scriptstyle {\hat {\sigma }}^{2}$ , is the MLE estimate for *σ*2.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The two estimators are quite similar in large samples; the first estimator is always unbiased, while the second estimator is biased but has a smaller mean squared error.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In practice *s*2 is used more often, since it is more convenient for the hypothesis testing.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The square root of *s*2 is called the *regression standard error*, *standard error of the regression*, or *standard error of the equation*.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] It is common to assess the goodness-of-fit of the OLS regression by comparing how much the initial variation in the sample can be reduced by regressing onto *X*.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where TSS is the *total sum of squares* for the dependent variable, ${\textstyle L=I_{n}-{\frac {1}{n}}J_{n}}$ , and ${\textstyle J_{n}}$ is an *n*×*n* matrix of ones.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In that case, *R*2 will always be a number between 0 and 1, with values close to 1 indicating a good degree of fit.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] If the data matrix *X* contains only two variables, a constant and a scalar regressor *xi*, then this is called the "simple regression model".
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This case is often considered in the beginner statistics classes, as it provides much simpler formulas even suitable for manual calculation.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In the previous section the least squares estimator ${\hat {\beta }}$ was obtained as a value that minimizes the sum of squared residuals of the model.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] However it is also possible to derive the same estimator from other approaches.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In all cases the formula for OLS estimator remains the same: ^*β* = (*X*T*X*)−1*X*T*y*; the only difference is in how we interpret this result.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] For mathematicians, OLS is an approximate solution to an overdetermined system of linear equations *Xβ* ≈ *y*, where *β* is the unknown.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Assuming the system cannot be solved exactly (the number of equations *n* is much larger than the number of unknowns *p*), we are looking for a solution that could provide the smallest discrepancy between the right- and left- hand sides.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where ‖·‖ is the standard *L*2 norm in the *n*-dimensional Euclidean space **R***n*.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The predicted quantity *Xβ* is just a certain linear combination of the vectors of regressors.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Thus, the residual vector *y* − *Xβ* will have the smallest length when *y* is projected orthogonally onto the linear subspace spanned by the columns of *X*.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The OLS estimator ${\hat {\beta }}$ in this case can be interpreted as the coefficients of vector decomposition of ^*y* = *Py* along the basis of *X*.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This means that $\mathbf {y} -\mathbf {X} {\boldsymbol {\hat {\beta }}}$ is the shortest of all possible vectors $\mathbf {y} -\mathbf {X} {\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ , that is, the variance of the residuals is the minimum possible.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Introducing ${\hat {\boldsymbol {\gamma }}}$ and a matrix *K* with the assumption that a matrix $[\mathbf {X} \ \mathbf {K} ]$ is non-singular and *K*T *X* = 0 (cf.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Another way of looking at it is to consider the regression line to be a weighted average of the lines passing through the combination of any two points in the dataset.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Although this way of calculation is more computationally expensive, it provides a better intuition on OLS.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The OLS estimator is identical to the maximum likelihood estimator (MLE) under the normality assumption for the error terms.[proof] This normality assumption has historical importance, as it provided the basis for the early work in linear regression analysis by Yule and Pearson.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] From the properties of MLE, we can infer that the OLS estimator is asymptotically efficient (in the sense of attaining the Cramér–Rao bound for variance) if the normality assumption is satisfied.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] These moment conditions state that the regressors should be uncorrelated with the errors.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Since *xi* is a *p*-vector, the number of moment conditions is equal to the dimension of the parameter vector *β*, and thus the system is exactly identified.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This is the so-called classical GMM case, when the estimator does not depend on the choice of the weighting matrix.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Note that the original strict exogeneity assumption E[*εi* | *xi*] = 0 implies a far richer set of moment conditions than stated above.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In particular, this assumption implies that for any vector-function ƒ, the moment condition E[*ƒ*(*xi*)·*εi*] = 0 will hold.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] However it can be shown using the Gauss–Markov theorem that the optimal choice of function ƒ is to take *ƒ*(*x*) = *x*, which results in the moment equation posted above.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] There are several different frameworks in which the linear regression model can be cast in order to make the OLS technique applicable.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Each of these settings produces the same formulas and same results.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The only difference is the interpretation and the assumptions which have to be imposed in order for the method to give meaningful results.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The choice of the applicable framework depends mostly on the nature of data in hand, and on the inference task which has to be performed.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] One of the lines of difference in interpretation is whether to treat the regressors as random variables, or as predefined constants.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In the first case (**random design**) the regressors *xi* are random and sampled together with the *yi*'s from some population, as in an observational study.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This approach allows for more natural study of the asymptotic properties of the estimators.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In the other interpretation (**fixed design**), the regressors *X* are treated as known constants set by a design, and *y* is sampled conditionally on the values of *X* as in an experiment.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] For practical purposes, this distinction is often unimportant, since estimation and inference is carried out while conditioning on *X*.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] All results stated in this article are within the random design framework.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The classical model focuses on the "finite sample" estimation and inference, meaning that the number of observations *n* is fixed.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This contrasts with the other approaches, which study the asymptotic behavior of OLS, and in which the behavior at a large number of samples is studied.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] To prove finite sample unbiasedness of the OLS estimator, we require the following assumptions.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Violations of these assumptions can result in biased estimations of ***β***, biased standard errors, untrustworthy confidence intervals and significance tests.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] If the strict exogeneity does not hold (as is the case with many time series models, where exogeneity is assumed only with respect to the past shocks but not the future ones), then these estimators will be biased in finite samples.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In particular, the standard error of each coefficient $\scriptstyle {\hat {\beta }}_{j}$ is equal to square root of the *j*-th diagonal element of this matrix.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The estimate of this standard error is obtained by replacing the unknown quantity *σ*2 with its estimate *s*2.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The *Gauss–Markov theorem* states that under the *spherical errors* assumption (that is, the errors should be uncorrelated and homoscedastic) the estimator $\scriptstyle {\hat {\beta }}$ is efficient in the class of linear unbiased estimators.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This is called the *best linear unbiased estimator* (BLUE).
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] in the sense that this is a nonnegative-definite matrix.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This theorem establishes optimality only in the class of linear unbiased estimators, which is quite restrictive.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Depending on the distribution of the error terms *ε*, other, non-linear estimators may provide better results than OLS.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The properties listed so far are all valid regardless of the underlying distribution of the error terms.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] However, if you are willing to assume that the *normality assumption* holds (that is, that *ε* ~ *N*(0, *σ*2*In*)), then additional properties of the OLS estimators can be stated.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This estimator reaches the Cramér–Rao bound for the model, and thus is optimal in the class of all unbiased estimators.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Note that unlike the Gauss–Markov theorem, this result establishes optimality among both linear and non-linear estimators, but only in the case of normally distributed error terms.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The variance of this estimator is equal to 2*σ*4/(*n* − *p*), which does not attain the Cramér–Rao bound of 2*σ*4/*n*.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] However it was shown that there are no unbiased estimators of *σ*2 with variance smaller than that of the estimator *s*2.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Moreover, the estimators $\scriptstyle {\hat {\beta }}$ and *s*2 are independent, the fact which comes in useful when constructing the t- and F-tests for the regression.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] As was mentioned before, the estimator ${\hat {\beta }}$ is linear in *y*, meaning that it represents a linear combination of the dependent variables *yi*.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The weights in this linear combination are functions of the regressors *X*, and generally are unequal.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The observations with high weights are called **influential** because they have a more pronounced effect on the value of the estimator.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] To analyze which observations are influential we remove a specific *j*-th observation and consider how much the estimated quantities are going to change (similarly to the jackknife method).
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *hj* = *xj*T (*X*T*X*)−1*xj* is the *j*-th diagonal element of the hat matrix *P*, and *xj* is the vector of regressors corresponding to the *j*-th observation.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] From the properties of the hat matrix, 0 ≤ *hj* ≤ 1, and they sum up to *p*, so that on average *hj* ≈ *p/n*.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] These quantities *hj* are called the **leverages**, and observations with high *hj* are called **leverage points**.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Usually the observations with high leverage ought to be scrutinized more carefully, in case they are erroneous, or outliers, or in some other way atypical of the rest of the dataset.
