[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The theorem can be used to establish a number of theoretical results.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] For example, having a regression with a constant and another regressor is equivalent to subtracting the means from the dependent variable and the regressor and then running the regression for the de-meaned variables but without the constant term.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The least squares estimators are point estimates of the linear regression model parameters *β*.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] However, generally we also want to know how close those estimates might be to the true values of parameters.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In other words, we want to construct the interval estimates.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Since we have not made any assumption about the distribution of error term *εi*, it is impossible to infer the distribution of the estimators ${\hat {\beta }}$ and ${\hat {\sigma }}^{2}$ .
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Nevertheless, we can apply the central limit theorem to derive their *asymptotic* properties as sample size *n* goes to infinity.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] While the sample size is necessarily finite, it is customary to assume that *n* is "large enough" so that the true distribution of the OLS estimator is close to its asymptotic limit.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *q* denotes the quantile function of standard normal distribution, and [·]*jj* is the *j*-th diagonal element of a matrix.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] These asymptotic distributions can be used for prediction, testing hypotheses, constructing other estimators, etc..
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] As an example consider the problem of prediction.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Suppose $x_{0}$ is some point within the domain of distribution of the regressors, and one wants to know what the response variable would have been at that point.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Two hypothesis tests are particularly widely used.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] First, one wants to know if the estimated regression equation is any better than simply predicting that all values of the response variable equal its sample mean (if not, it is said to have no explanatory power).
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The null hypothesis of no explanatory value of the estimated regression is tested using an F-test.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] If the calculated F-value is found to be large enough to exceed its critical value for the pre-chosen level of significance, the null hypothesis is rejected and the alternative hypothesis, that the regression has explanatory power, is accepted.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Otherwise, the null hypothesis of no explanatory power is accepted.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Second, for each explanatory variable of interest, one wants to know whether its estimated coefficient differs significantly from zero—that is, whether this particular explanatory variable in fact has explanatory power in predicting the response variable.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Here the null hypothesis is that the true coefficient is zero.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This hypothesis is tested by computing the coefficient's t-statistic, as the ratio of the coefficient estimate to its standard error.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] If the t-statistic is larger than a predetermined value, the null hypothesis is rejected and the variable is found to have explanatory power, with its coefficient significantly different from zero.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Otherwise, the null hypothesis of a zero value of the true coefficient is accepted.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In addition, the Chow test is used to test whether two subsamples both have the same underlying true coefficient values.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The sum of squared residuals of regressions on each of the subsets and on the combined data set are compared by computing an F-statistic; if this exceeds a critical value, the null hypothesis of no difference between the two subsets is rejected; otherwise, it is accepted.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In a time series model, we require the stochastic process {*xi*, *yi*} to be stationary and ergodic; if {*xi*, *yi*} is nonstationary, OLS results are often biased unless {*xi*, *yi*} is co-integrating.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] We still require the regressors to be *strictly exogenous*: E[*xiεi*] = 0 for all *i* = 1, ..., *n*.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Finally, the assumptions on the variance take the form of requiring that {*xiεi*} is a martingale difference sequence, with a finite matrix of second moments *Q**xxε*² = E[ *εi*2*xi xi*T ].
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *Q* is a *p*×*q* matrix of full rank, and *c* is a *q*×1 vector of known constants, where *q < p*.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In this case least squares estimation is equivalent to minimizing the sum of squared residuals of the model subject to the constraint *A*.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This expression for the constrained estimator is valid as long as the matrix *XTX* is invertible.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] It was assumed from the beginning of this article that this matrix is of full rank, and it was noted that when the rank condition fails, *β* will not be identifiable.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] However it may happen that adding the restriction *A* makes *β* identifiable, in which case one would like to find the formula for the estimator.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *R* is a *p*×(*p* − *q*) matrix such that the matrix [*Q R*] is non-singular, and *RTQ* = 0.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Such a matrix can always be found, although generally it is not unique.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The second formula coincides with the first in case when *XTX* is invertible.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] The following data set gives average heights and weights for American women aged 30–39 (source: *The World Almanac and Book of Facts, 1975*).
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] When only one dependent variable is being modeled, a scatterplot will suggest the form and strength of the relationship between the dependent variable and regressors.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] It might also reveal outliers, heteroscedasticity, and other aspects of the data that may complicate the interpretation of a fitted regression model.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] The scatterplot suggests that the relationship is strong and can be approximated as a quadratic function.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] OLS can handle non-linear relationships by introducing the regressor *HEIGHT*2.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] Ordinary least squares analysis often includes the use of diagnostic plots designed to detect departures of the data from the assumed form of the model.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] An important consideration when carrying out statistical inference using regression models is how the data were sampled.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] In this example, the data are averages rather than measurements on individual women.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] The fit of the model is very good, but this does not imply that the weight of an individual woman can be predicted with high accuracy based only on her height.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] This example also demonstrates that coefficients determined by these calculations are sensitive to how the data is prepared.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] The heights were originally given rounded to the nearest inch and have been converted and rounded to the nearest centimetre.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] Since the conversion factor is one inch to 2.54 cm this is *not* an exact conversion.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] The original inches can be recovered by Round(x/0.0254) and then re-converted to metric without rounding.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] Using either of these equations to predict the weight of a 5' 6" (1.6764 m) woman gives similar values: 62.94 kg with rounding vs.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] Thus a seemingly small variation in the data has a real effect on the coefficients but a small effect on the results of the equation.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] While this may look innocuous in the middle of the data range it could become significant at the extremes or in the case where the fitted model is used to project outside the data range (extrapolation).
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] This highlights a common error: this example is an abuse of OLS which inherently requires that the errors in the independent variable (in this case height) are zero or at least negligible.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] The initial rounding to nearest inch plus any actual measurement errors constitute a finite and non-negligible error.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] As a result, the fitted parameters are not the best estimates they are presumed to be.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] Though not totally spurious the error in the estimation will depend upon relative size of the *x* and *y* errors.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] We can use the least square mechanism to figure out the equation of a two body orbit in polar base co-ordinates.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] The equation typically used is $r(\theta )={\frac {p}{1-e\cos(\theta )}}$ where $r(\theta )$ is the radius of how far the object is from one of the bodies.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] In the equation the parameters p and e are used to determine the path of the orbit.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] We need to find the least-squares approximation of e and p for the given data.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] First we need to represent e and p in a linear form.
[src:statsmodels/ordinary-least-squares-p02] Furthermore, one could fit for apsides by expanding $\cos(\theta )$ with an extra parameter as $\cos(\theta -\theta _{0})=\cos(\theta )\cos(\theta _{0})+\sin(\theta )\sin(\theta _{0})$ , which is linear in both $\cos(\theta )$ and in the extra basis function $\sin(\theta )$ .
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] The most common form of regression analysis is linear regression, in which one finds the line (or a more complex linear combination) that most closely fits the data according to a specific mathematical criterion.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] For example, the method of ordinary least squares computes the unique line (or hyperplane) that minimizes the sum of squared differences between the true data and that line (or hyperplane).
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] For specific mathematical reasons (see linear regression), this allows the researcher to estimate the conditional expectation (or population average value) of the dependent variable when the independent variables take on a given set of values.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Less common forms of regression use slightly different procedures to estimate alternative location parameters (e.g., quantile regression or Necessary Condition Analysis) or estimate the conditional expectation across a broader collection of non-linear models (e.g., nonparametric regression).
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Regression analysis is primarily used for two conceptually distinct purposes.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] First, regression analysis is widely used for prediction and forecasting, where its use has substantial overlap with the field of machine learning.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Second, in some situations regression analysis can be used to infer causal relationships between the independent and dependent variables.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Importantly, regressions by themselves only reveal relationships between a dependent variable and a collection of independent variables in a fixed dataset.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] To use regressions for prediction or to infer causal relationships, respectively, a researcher must carefully justify why existing relationships have predictive power for a new context or why a relationship between two variables has a causal interpretation.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] The latter is especially important when researchers hope to estimate causal relationships using observational data.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] He also distinguished between two inhomogeneous sets of data and might have thought of an *optimal* solution in terms of bias, though not in terms of effectiveness." He previously used an averaging method in his 1671 work on Newton's rings, which was unprecedented at the time.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] The method of least squares was published by Legendre in 1805, and by Gauss in 1809.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Legendre and Gauss both applied the method to the problem of determining, from astronomical observations, the orbits of bodies about the Sun (mostly comets, but also later the then newly discovered minor planets).
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Gauss published a further development of the theory of least squares in 1821, including a version of the Gauss–Markov theorem.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] The term "regression" was coined by Francis Galton in the 19th century to describe a biological phenomenon.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] The phenomenon was that the heights of descendants of tall ancestors tend to regress down towards a normal average (a phenomenon also known as regression toward the mean).
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] For Galton, regression had only this biological meaning, but his work was later extended by Udny Yule and Karl Pearson to a more general statistical context.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] In the work of Yule and Pearson, the joint distribution of the response and explanatory variables is assumed to be Gaussian.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Fisher assumed that the conditional distribution of the response variable is Gaussian, but the joint distribution need not be.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] In this respect, Fisher's assumption is closer to Gauss's formulation of 1821.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] In the 1950s and 1960s, economists used electromechanical desk calculators to calculate regressions.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Before 1970, it sometimes took up to 24 hours to receive the result from one regression.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Regression methods continue to be an area of active research.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Modern regression analysis is typically done with statistical and spreadsheet software packages on computers as well as on handheld scientific and graphing calculators.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] In practice, researchers first select a model they would like to estimate and then use their chosen method (e.g., ordinary least squares) to estimate the parameters of that model.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] In various fields of application, different terminologies are used in place of dependent and independent variables.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] In the standard regression model, the independent variables $X_{i}$ are assumed to be free of error.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] The errors-in-variables model can be used if the independent variables are assumed to contain errors.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Other modifications to the standard regression model can be made to account for various scenarios, such as situations involving omitted variables, confounding variables or endogeneity.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] The researchers' goal is to estimate the function $f(X_{i},\beta )$ that most closely fits the data.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] To carry out regression analysis, the form of the function f must be specified.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Sometimes the form of this function is based on knowledge about the relationship between $Y_{i}$ and $X_{i}$ that does not rely on the data.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] If no such knowledge is available, a flexible or convenient form for f is chosen.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] For example, a simple univariate regression may propose $f(X_{i},\beta )=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}X_{i}$ , suggesting that the researcher believes $Y_{i}=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}X_{i}+e_{i}$ to be a reasonable approximation for the statistical process generating the data.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Once researchers determine their preferred statistical model, different forms of regression analysis provide tools to estimate the parameters $\beta$ .
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] For example, least squares (including its most common variant, ordinary least squares) finds the value of $\beta$ that minimizes the sum of squared errors $\sum _{i}(Y_{i}-f(X_{i},\beta ))^{2}$ .
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] A given regression method will ultimately provide an estimate of $\beta$ , usually denoted ${\hat {\beta }}$ to distinguish the estimate from the true (unknown) parameter value that generated the data.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Using this estimate, the researcher can then use the *fitted value* ${\hat {Y_{i}}}=f(X_{i},{\hat {\beta }})$ for prediction or to assess the accuracy of the model in explaining the data.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Whether the researcher is intrinsically interested in the estimate ${\hat {\beta }}$ or the predicted value ${\hat {Y_{i}}}$ will depend on context and their goals.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] As described in ordinary least squares, least squares is widely used because the estimated function $f(X_{i},{\hat {\beta }})$ approximates the conditional expectation $E(Y_{i}|X_{i})$ .
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] However, alternative variants (e.g., least absolute deviations or quantile regression) are useful when researchers want to model other functions $f(X_{i},\beta )$ .
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] There must be sufficient data to estimate a regression model.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] For example, suppose that a researcher has access to N rows of data with one dependent and two independent variables: $(Y_{i},X_{1i},X_{2i})$ .
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Suppose further that the researcher wants to estimate a bivariate linear model via least squares: $Y_{i}=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}X_{1i}+\beta _{2}X_{2i}+e_{i}$ .
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] To understand why there are infinitely many options, note that the system of $N=2$ equations is to be solved for 3 unknowns, which makes the system underdetermined.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Alternatively, one can visualize infinitely many 3-dimensional planes that go through $N=2$ fixed points.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] More generally, to estimate a least squares model with k distinct parameters, one must have $N\geq k$ distinct data points.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] If $N>k$ , then there does not generally exist a set of parameters that will perfectly fit the data.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] The quantity $N-k$ appears often in regression analysis, and is referred to as the degrees of freedom in the model.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Moreover, to estimate a least squares model, the independent variables $(X_{1i},X_{2i},...,X_{ki})$ must be linearly independent: one must *not* be able to reconstruct any of the independent variables by adding and multiplying the remaining independent variables.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] As discussed in ordinary least squares, this condition ensures that $X^{T}X$ is an invertible matrix and therefore that a unique solution ${\hat {\beta }}$ exists.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] By itself, a regression is just a computation performed on a set of data.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] In order to interpret the resultant regression as a meaningful statistical model that quantifies real-world relationships, researchers often rely on a number of classical assumptions.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] A handful of conditions are sufficient for the least-squares estimator to possess desirable properties: in particular, the Gauss–Markov assumptions imply that the parameter estimates will be unbiased, consistent, and efficient in the class of linear unbiased estimators.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Practitioners have developed a variety of methods to maintain some or all of these desirable properties in real-world settings, because these classical assumptions are unlikely to hold exactly.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] For example, modeling errors-in-variables can lead to reasonable estimates independent variables are measured with errors.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Heteroscedasticity-consistent standard errors allow the variance of $e_{i}$ to change across values of $X_{i}$ .
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Correlated errors that exist within subsets of the data or follow specific patterns can be handled using *clustered standard errors, geographic weighted regression*, or Newey–West standard errors, among other techniques.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] When rows of data correspond to locations in space, the choice of how to model $e_{i}$ within geographic units can have important consequences.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] The subfield of econometrics is largely focused on developing techniques that allow researchers to make reasonable real-world conclusions in real-world settings, where classical assumptions do not hold exactly.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] In linear regression, the model specification is that the dependent variable, $y_{i}$ is a linear combination of the *parameters* (but need not be linear in the *independent variables*).
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] In multiple linear regression, there are several independent variables or functions of independent variables.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] In both cases, $\varepsilon _{i}$ is an error term and the subscript i indexes a particular observation.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] The residual, $e_{i}=y_{i}-{\widehat {y}}_{i}$ , is the difference between the value of the dependent variable predicted by the model, ${\widehat {y}}_{i}$ , and the true value of the dependent variable, $y_{i}$ .
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] One method of estimation is ordinary least squares.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Minimization of this function results in a set of normal equations, a set of simultaneous linear equations in the parameters, which are solved to yield the parameter estimators, ${\widehat {\beta }}_{0},{\widehat {\beta }}_{1}$ .
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] where ${\bar {x}}$ is the mean (average) of the x values and ${\bar {y}}$ is the mean of the y values.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] This is called the mean square error (MSE) of the regression.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] The denominator is the sample size reduced by the number of model parameters estimated from the same data, $(n-p)$ for p regressors or $(n-p-1)$ if an intercept is used.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] In this case, $p=1$ so the denominator is $n-2$ .
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Under the further assumption that the population error term is normally distributed, the researcher can use these estimated standard errors to create confidence intervals and conduct hypothesis tests about the population parameters.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] where $x_{ij}$ is the i -th observation on the j -th independent variable.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] If the first independent variable takes the value 1 for all i , $x_{i1}=1$ , then $\beta _{1}$ is called the regression intercept.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] The least squares parameter estimates are obtained from p normal equations.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] where the $ij$ element of $\mathbf {X}$ is $x_{ij}$ , the i element of the column vector Y is $y_{i}$ , and the j element of ${\hat {\boldsymbol {\beta }}}$ is ${\hat {\beta }}_{j}$ .
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Once a regression model has been constructed, it may be important to confirm the goodness of fit of the model and the statistical significance of the estimated parameters.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Commonly used checks of goodness of fit include the R-squared, analyses of the pattern of residuals and hypothesis testing.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Statistical significance can be checked by an F-test of the overall fit, followed by t-tests of individual parameters.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Interpretations of these diagnostic tests rest heavily on the model's assumptions.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Although examination of the residuals can be used to invalidate a model, the results of a t-test or F-test are sometimes more difficult to interpret if the model's assumptions are violated.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] For example, if the error term does not have a normal distribution, in small samples the estimated parameters will not follow normal distributions and complicate inference.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] With relatively large samples, however, a central limit theorem can be invoked such that hypothesis testing may proceed using asymptotic approximations.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Limited dependent variables, which are response variables that are categorical or constrained to fall only in a certain range, often arise in econometrics.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] The response variable may be non-continuous ("limited" to lie on some subset of the real line).
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] For binary (zero or one) variables, if analysis proceeds with least-squares linear regression, the model is called the linear probability model.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Nonlinear models for binary dependent variables include the probit and logit model.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] The multivariate probit model is a standard method of estimating a joint relationship between several binary dependent variables and some independent variables.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] For categorical variables with more than two values there is the multinomial logit.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] For ordinal variables with more than two values, there are the ordered logit and ordered probit models.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Censored regression models may be used when the dependent variable is only sometimes observed, and Heckman correction type models may be used when the sample is not randomly selected from the population of interest.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] An alternative to such procedures is linear regression based on polychoric correlation (or polyserial correlations) between the categorical variables.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Such procedures differ in the assumptions made about the distribution of the variables in the population.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] If the variable is positive with low values and represents the repetition of the occurrence of an event, then count models like the Poisson regression or the negative binomial model may be used.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] When the model function is not linear in the parameters, the sum of squares must be minimized by an iterative procedure.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] This introduces many complications which are summarized in Differences between linear and non-linear least squares.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Regression models ***predict*** a value of the *Y* variable given known values of the *X* variables.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Prediction *within* the range of values in the dataset used for model-fitting is known informally as *interpolation*.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Prediction *outside* this range of the data is known as *extrapolation*.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Performing extrapolation relies strongly on the regression assumptions.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] The further the extrapolation goes outside the data, the more room there is for the model to fail due to differences between the assumptions and the sample data or the true values.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] A *prediction interval* that represents the uncertainty may accompany the point prediction.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Such intervals tend to expand rapidly as the values of the independent variable(s) moved outside the range covered by the observed data.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] For such reasons and others, some tend to say that it might be unwise to undertake extrapolation.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] The assumption of a particular form for the relation between *Y* and *X* is another source of uncertainty.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] A properly conducted regression analysis will include an assessment of how well the assumed form is matched by the observed data, but it can only do so within the range of values of the independent variables actually available.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] This means that any extrapolation is particularly reliant on the assumptions being made about the structural form of the regression relationship.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] If this knowledge includes the fact that the dependent variable cannot go outside a certain range of values, this can be made use of in selecting the model – even if the observed dataset has no values particularly near such bounds.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] The implications of this step of choosing an appropriate functional form for the regression can be great when extrapolation is considered.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] At a minimum, it can ensure that any extrapolation arising from a fitted model is "realistic" (or in accord with what is known).
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] There are no generally agreed methods for relating the number of observations versus the number of independent variables in the model.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] One method conjectured by Good and Hardin is $N=m^{n}$ , where N is the sample size, n is the number of independent variables and m is the number of observations needed to reach the desired precision if the model had only one independent variable.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] For example, a researcher is building a linear regression model using a dataset that contains 1000 patients ( N ).
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] All major statistical software packages perform least squares regression analysis and inference.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Simple linear regression and multiple regression using least squares can be done in some spreadsheet applications and on some calculators.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] While many statistical software packages can perform various types of nonparametric and robust regression, these methods are less standardized.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Different software packages implement different methods, and a method with a given name may be implemented differently in different packages.
[src:statsmodels/regression-analysis] Specialized regression software has been developed for use in fields such as survey analysis and neuroimaging.
[src:statsmodels/regression] Linear models with independently and identically distributed errors, and for errors with heteroscedasticity or autocorrelation.
[src:statsmodels/regression] This module allows estimation by ordinary least squares (OLS), weighted least squares (WLS), generalized least squares (GLS), and feasible generalized least squares with autocorrelated AR(p) errors.
[src:statsmodels/regression] See Module Reference for commands and arguments.
[src:statsmodels/regression] All regression models define the same methods and follow the same structure, and can be used in a similar fashion.
[src:statsmodels/regression] Some of them contain additional model specific methods and attributes.
[src:statsmodels/regression] GLS is the superclass of the other regression classes except for RecursiveLS, RollingWLS and RollingOLS.
[src:statsmodels/regression] The *p* x *n* Moore-Penrose pseudoinverse of the whitened design matrix.
[src:statsmodels/regression] This is equal to *p* - 1, where *p* is the number of regressors.
[src:statsmodels/regression] Note that the intercept is not counted as using a degree of freedom here.
[src:statsmodels/regression] This is equal *n - p* where *n* is the number of observations and *p* is the number of parameters.
[src:statsmodels/regression] Note that the intercept is counted as using a degree of freedom here.
[src:statsmodels/regression] The value of the likelihood function of the fitted model.
[src:statsmodels/regression] The *n* x *n* covariance matrix of the error terms: \(\epsilon\sim N\left(0,\Sigma\right)\).
[src:statsmodels/regression] The whitened design matrix \(\Psi^{T}X\).
[src:statsmodels/regression] The whitened response variable \(\Psi^{T}Y\).
[src:statsmodels/regression] Fitting a linear regression model returns a results class.
[src:statsmodels/regression] OLS has a specific results class with some additional methods compared to the results class of the other linear models.
